
# pdt-sage-verification

End-to-end verification of the foundational numerical claims of Pisot
Dimensional Theory (PDT), using only SageMath's standard mathematical
libraries. Runs in under a minute on standard hardware.

## What this repository verifies

A single SageMath script (`pdt_verification.sage`, approximately 70 lines)
performs the following verifications in sequence:

1. **Pisot boundary constants.** Computes ρ ≈ 1.3247 as the real root of
   x³ − x − 1 and Q ≈ 1.2207 as the real root of x⁴ − x − 1.

2. **Elliptic curves.** Loads Cremona 368f1 and 1132b1 from Sage's elliptic
   curve database and verifies conductors, ranks, and discriminants.

3. **Real periods.** Computes Ω₃ = 2.19658... (real period of E₃ = 368f1)
   and Ω₄ = 2.71218... (real period of E₄ = 1132b1).

4. **Strong coupling.** Verifies α_s(M_Z) = Ω₄ / 23 = 0.11792 against the
   PDG value 0.1179 (error 0.0175%).

5. **L-function special values.** Computes L(E₃, 1) and L'(E₄, 1), which
   confirm BSD for both curves.

6. **Weak mixing angle.** Verifies sin²θ_W = L(E₃, 1) · L'(E₄, 1) / 23
   against the measured value (error 0.0083%).

7. **Barbero-Immirzi parameter.** Verifies γ_BI = λ₄ · ρ = 0.23954 against
   the Meissner value (error 0.0023%).

8. **Number field invariants.** Computes the discriminant, class number,
   and regulator of Q(ρ) and Q(Q). Confirms that Reg(Q(ρ)) / ln(ρ) = 1
   exactly — the regulator of the 3D number field equals the logarithm
   of the plastic constant.

9. **Compositum.** Constructs the degree-12 compositum Q(ρ, Q) and
   computes its discriminant.

10. **Unit-norm identity.** Verifies the foundational algebraic identity
    N(ρ · Q) = −1 in the compositum Q(ρ, Q). This is the bedrock
    identity underlying the entire PDT framework.

## Requirements

- SageMath 9.0 or newer.

No other dependencies. All computations use Sage's built-in elliptic
curve, L-function, and number field implementations. No PDT-specific
code is used anywhere in the script.

## How to run

### Option 1 — SageMathCell (no installation required)

The fastest way to run this verification is through SageMathCell, which
runs SageMath in your browser with no setup:

1. Open https://sagecell.sagemath.org
2. Paste the contents of `pdt_verification.sage` into the cell
3. Click "Evaluate"

The full verification typically completes in 30-60 seconds. SageMathCell
has a default execution time limit; if the compositum step times out,
use one of the options below.

### Option 2 — Local SageMath installation### Option 3 — Jupyter notebook with SageMath kernel

Paste the contents of `pdt_verification.sage` into a cell and execute.

### Option 4 — CoCalc or other hosted SageMath environment

Upload the script or paste it into a notebook cell. CoCalc (https://cocalc.com) provides free SageMath access with no time limits.

## Expected output

See `expected_output.txt` for a reference run. A correct run should match every line up to rounding in the final digits. Specifically:

- α_s = Ω₄/23 should match the PDG value to better than 0.02%.
- sin²θ_W from L-functions should match to better than 0.01%.
- γ_BI = λ₄·ρ should match to better than 0.003%.
- Reg(Q(ρ)) / ln(ρ) should equal 1 to machine precision.
- N(ρ · Q) should equal −1 exactly (it is an integer in the compositum, not an approximation).

If any of these fail, something has changed in Sage's underlying implementations and the discrepancy is worth investigating.

## What this script does not do

This is a verification script, not a derivation script. It confirms that the numerical predictions of PDT agree with standard mathematical computations. It does not derive the formulas themselves — those derivations appear in the PDT papers listed below.

This script also does not attempt to test every PDT prediction. It covers the foundational claims that establish the framework. Extended verifications of the full Lagrangian, the cosmological sector, and the Standard Model parameter table appear in separate repositories.

